{"key":"post-16169948","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>16169948</id>\n<content>&lt;/font&gt;&lt;blockquote&gt;&lt;font class=&quot;small&quot;&gt;Quote:&lt;/font&gt;&lt;hr /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;The one Pro I like about it is that after inoculating and shaking very well the spores take in many parts of the jar rather then taking in 2-5spots having to wait a week or so to shake.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;hr /&gt;&lt;/blockquote&gt;&lt;font class=&quot;post&quot;&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Exactly.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;And, this is why you shouldn't do it.&amp;nbsp; Instead of the mycelium starting out in a few places, it starts out in hundreds, with hundreds or even thousands of different strains, many of which are non-compatible.&amp;nbsp; This means instead of a coherent organism at fruiting time, you have hundreds of strains, each holding onto a piece of substrate the size of a thimble.&amp;nbsp; This is why fruiting performance is usually poor with dark syringes and the reason experienced growers always use the fewest spores possible.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;The problem which perpetuates this myth is a few unscrupulous shysters who sell dark syringes because they know noobs will pay extra for them because it's mostly non-experienced noobs who buy spore syringes.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;In addition, you should never shake after inoculating with spores.&amp;nbsp; You should let them germinate and 'mate' to form dikaryons before the first shake.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>16169968</next>\n<prev>16169934</prev>\n<first>16169075</first>\n<last>16224826</last>\n<when>1335966288</when>\n<utime>05/02/12 04:44 PM</utime>\n</post>"}